[size=18pt][b][color=#27ae60]The SEC Privacy Roundtable and Our Position[/color][/b][/size]

On December 15, 2025, the SEC's Crypto Task Force held a historic roundtable on [b]"Financial Surveillance and Privacy"[/b] — the first time U.S. regulators have publicly treated crypto privacy as a legitimate policy discussion rather than just an enforcement target.

[quote]"Protecting one's privacy should be the norm, not an indicator of criminal intent."
[i]— SEC Commissioner Hester Peirce[/i][/quote]

Q-NarwhalKnight was built on a single axiom:

[center][b][size=14pt]No one should be forced to expose their economic life in order to participate in society.[/size][/b][/center]

We reject "opt-in privacy" — it creates two classes of users: those who are [i]visible[/i] and those who are [i]suspicious[/i]. When privacy is optional, using it becomes a signal. Our approach:

[list]
[li][color=#2ecc71][b]✓[/b][/color] All transactions are private — no "transparent mode"[/li]
[li][color=#2ecc71][b]✓[/b][/color] All balances are private — no public ledger exposure[/li]
[li][color=#2ecc71][b]✓[/b][/color] All metadata is minimized — Tor integration, Dandelion++ gossip[/li]
[li][color=#2ecc71][b]✓[/b][/color] Post-quantum by default — protecting against future threats[/li]
[/list]

[url=https://quillon.xyz/downloads/qnk-privacy-philosophy-whitepaper.pdf][b]Read the Privacy Philosophy Whitepaper[/b][/url]

